<subSubSection id="8C11C86B3C99860382A19E73D4351D55" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="CA4F5264B40E9AD2FAD10F8E079D4188" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F8DBF204F7311FAC8304E0DCC4E424C" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
Usually, the trunk width is given as the maximum trunk widthwhich is at the midgut level. In this case, the type specimen 
<taxonomicName id="B5CA3D627F6A054FD994BBE7056D9C7A" genus="H." lsidName="H. ooeides" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="ooeides">
H. 
<normalizedToken id="AC7EB3AA480BEB15DBBEC021C173E8A0" originalValue="ooëides">ooeides</normalizedToken>
</taxonomicName>
is 42 
<normalizedToken id="30534DBAAA3FC4AC3F03B7D274EFBD5B" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
wide. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="969961BA8E53D94908CCA1030E4E78B9" author="Brunson, RB" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Microscopical Society" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" pagination="325 - 352" title="An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3223127" volume="69" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
measured the trunk width posterior to the midgut level (close to the posterior end of the body) and found it to be 36 
<normalizedToken id="CB111C6E5ED17AC5EF92AFA854EF5E0A" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C454DF65944D796AC9A3A1BF51D54BE2" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
Differences in spines length between the original description and the present one (Table 1) are due to different measurement methods. We chose to measure each spine length outlining its curvature (100, 90, 75, 90, 82, 80 
<normalizedToken id="320E1AC6D816A59A9DA300088F48DCAB" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
respectively) instead of measuring the distance between the spine base insertion and apex as a straight line, as 
<bibRefCitation id="915A08350AB43F9EACE40A6231C5D910" author="Brunson, RB" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Microscopical Society" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" pagination="325 - 352" title="An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3223127" volume="69" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
did (86, 86, 67, 82, 82 and 58 
<normalizedToken id="07FC284A1E04FC48ABC793F7423C5C76" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, respectively).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D5B339C5968C97D3EB3AEC5BC403FC23" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
Additionally, the original description mentions a pair of caudal bristles (Figure 2C) that originate 10 
<normalizedToken id="5682A4FB33EC144D81D1DBABBE9CB018" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
from the posterior end of the trunk. After reexamination of the type specimen (Figure 2A, 
<normalizedToken id="D2AD2CC8934D34C3A31CCB23DF914037" originalValue="B–D">B-D</normalizedToken>
) we conclude that 
<bibRefCitation id="820A3DA63714AAE7D0B62885217667E6" author="Brunson, RB" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Microscopical Society" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" pagination="325 - 352" title="An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3223127" volume="69" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
may have misinterpreted these structures. In fact, our observations revealed that the caudal bristles described by 
<bibRefCitation id="F94F189484053DEFE8BEB60709BD9515" author="Brunson, RB" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Microscopical Society" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" pagination="325 - 352" title="An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3223127" volume="69" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
actually are the ta1 spines, due to their similar position relative to the posterior trunk, size and shape (Figure 2A, B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="472F5B3332F2273D3F5C97320E7ABBA5" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
As previously mentioned, the description of some morphological characters of 
<taxonomicName id="34795D57F4CB5227D8F405667750EF50" genus="H." lsidName="H. ooeides" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="ooeides">
H. 
<normalizedToken id="6D4D5B844CD2B666293BEDC7290CD331" originalValue="ooëides">ooeides</normalizedToken>
</taxonomicName>
were misinterpreted by 
<bibRefCitation id="FB138160C36EFA68998F37CE899875B5" author="Brunson, RB" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Microscopical Society" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" pagination="325 - 352" title="An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3223127" volume="69" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
and incorrectly replicated by 
<bibRefCitation id="AC4D59FB8284753FE99D61E62959A08A" author="Balsamo, M" journalOrPublisher="Backhuys Publishers, Margraf Publishers, Weikersheim" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" title="Gastrotricha: biology, ecology and systematics. Families Dasydytidae, Dichaeturidae, Neogosseidae, Proichthydiidae." year="2014">Balsamo et al. (2014)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="71EFBCC9C48FA2121AF66AE382A27579" author="Minowa, AK" journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" pagination="100 - 109" title="A new species of Haltidytes Remane, 1936 (Gastrotricha: Chaetonotida: Dasydytidae) from an urban lagoon in Brazil with a phylogenetic reconstruction of the genus based on morphological data." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jcz.2017.08.003" volume="269" year="2017">Minowa and Garraffoni (2017)</bibRefCitation>
. We address this issue by correcting the taxonomic key 
<taxonomicName id="379C83E4F06202DBF9D3E700560D8B42" family="Dasydytidae" genus="Haltidytes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haltidytes" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="genus">Haltidytes</taxonomicName>
in order to correct previous misinterpretations.
</paragraph>
